SIMPLE: steal
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Steal
<hw>Steal</hw> <pr>(st⟦emac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Stale</er> a handle.]</ety> <def>A handle; a stale, or stele.</def>
<mark>[Archaic or Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And in his hand a huge poleax did bear.⟦br⟧
Whose <qex>steale</qex> was iron-studded but not long.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Steal
<hw>Steal</hw> <pr>(st⟦emac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Stole</conjf> <pr>(st⟦omac⟧l)</pr>;
<pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Stolen</conjf> <pr>(st⟦omac⟧"l'n)</pr>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Stealing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stelen</ets>, AS. <ets>stelan</ets>; akin to OFries.
<ets>stela</ets>, D. <ets>stelen</ets>, OHG. <ets>stelan</ets>, G.
<ets>stehlen</ets>, Icel. <ets>stela</ets>, SW. <ets>stj⟦aum⟧la</ets>,
Dan. <ets>stiaele</ets>, Goth. <ets>stilan</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To take, and carry away, feloniously; to take without right or
leave, and with intent to keep wrongfully; <as>as, to <ex>steal</ex> the
personal goods of another</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Maugre thy heed, thou must for indigence⟦br⟧
Or <qex>steal</qex>, or beg, or borrow, thy dispense.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The man who <qex>stole</qex> a goose and gave away the giblets in
alms.</q> <rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1408 pr=VMG --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To withdraw or convey clandestinely (reflexive);
hence, to creep furtively, or to insinuate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They could insinuate and <qex>steal</qex> themselves under the
same by their humble carriage and submission.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will <qex>steal</qex> himself into a man's favor.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To gain by insinuating arts or covert
means.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So Absalom <qex>stole</qex> the hearts of the men of Israel.</q>
<rj><qau>2 Sam. xv. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To get into one's power gradually and by
imperceptible degrees; to take possession of by a gradual and
imperceptible appropriation; -- with <xex>away</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Variety of objects has a tendency to <qex>steal</qex> away the
mind from its steady pursuit of any subject.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To accomplish in a concealed or unobserved manner;
to try to carry out secretly; <as>as, to <ex>steal</ex> a
look</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Always, when thou changest thine opinion or course, profess it
plainly, . . . and do not think to <qex>steal</qex> it.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To steal a march</b></col>, <cd>to march in a covert way;
to gain an advantage unobserved; -- formerly followed by <xex>of</xex>,
but now by <xex>on</xex> or <xex>upon</xex>, and sometimes by
<xex>over</xex>; as, <xex>to steal a march</xex> upon one's political
rivals.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She yesterday wanted <qex>to steal a march</qex> of poor
Liddy.</q> <rj><qau>Smollett.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fifty thousand men can not easily <qex>steal a march</qex> over
the sea.</q> <rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To filch; pilfer; purloin; thieve.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Steal
<hw>Steal</hw> <pr>(st⟦emac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To practice, or be guilty of, theft; to commit larceny or
theft.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt not <qex>steal</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xx.
15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To withdraw, or pass privily; to slip in, along, or
away, unperceived; to go or come furtively.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fixed of mind to avoid further entreaty, and to fly all company,
one night she <qex>stole</qex> away.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From whom you now must <qex>steal</qex>, and take no leave.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A soft and solemn breathing sound⟦br⟧
Rose like a steam of rich, distilled perfumes,⟦br⟧
And <qex>stole</qex> upon the air.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stealer</ent>⟦br⟧
